@niketh segments are removed here: https://github.com/druid-io/druid/blob/master/server/src/main/java/io/druid/server/coordinator/helper/DruidCoordinatorBalancer.java#L185.

It's not that *all* segments *must* be removed in this loop: https://github.com/druid-io/druid/blob/master/server/src/main/java/io/druid/server/coordinator/helper/DruidCoordinatorBalancer.java#L122. Note that this loop is limited to `maxSegmentsToMove` steps, that comes from config and that generally could be less than `currentlyMovingSegments.size()`. It's supposed that `currentlyMovingSegments` becomes empty over several distinct calls to `DruidCoordinatorBalancer.run()`.

Also I'm not sure that it's actually bad if `currentlyMovingSegments` never becomes empty (because there are always more segments to move). It won't "reduce lifetimes" (I don't really understand what does it mean), but is that bad?

@niketh 
> For those that are in "else" have to be removed, and in the PR code that "else statement" has been removed

It's not a "side effect" of this PR, it's actually the very purpose of this PR that is reflected in the title: **Do not remove segments from currentlyMovingSegments in DruidBalancer if move is impossible or not needed**. We think it's wrong to remove segments in this case. Why do you think segments "have to be" removed in this case?

@leventov 

> "We think it's wrong to remove segments in this case. Why do you think segments "have to be" removed in this case?"

Because if currentlyMovingSegments is not empty a new assignment cycle of DruidBalancer will not happen

Broken in the sense that if you have double columns, SQL stuff won't work right. The UTs are passing since they don't test double columns. But there's code like this:

```java
  public static StringComparator getStringComparatorForSqlTypeName(SqlTypeName sqlTypeName)
  {
    final ValueType valueType = getValueTypeForSqlTypeName(sqlTypeName);
    if (valueType == ValueType.LONG || valueType == ValueType.FLOAT) {
      return StringComparators.NUMERIC;
    } else {
      return StringComparators.LEXICOGRAPHIC;
    }
  }
```

Which needs to get cleaned up since it would lead to wrong results. Probably also this kind of code should be changed to throw an error on unrecognized ValueTypes, in case we add new ones in the future, since errors are better than wrong results.
